snippet.textDisplay: When Deborah mentioned her distaste at the branding, I thought James should have used his name but he did it, (in my opinion) absolutely correctly .. by James Cadbury.  I fail to see how Mondelez (the owner of the Cadbury brand) could possibly sue someone for using his own name.  None of the colours or fonts in any way even hint at the Cadbury brand, indeed in his position, I would add a little story to the rear packaging about how his great great grandfather started the company mentioning that it is today owned by Mondelez.  I agree with Peter that they should have a go at him as this would give a huge amount of free publicity, possibly without the possibility of Mondelez seeing a return on their legal 'investment'.  I very much doubt that this multinational would take this action knowing what the effect would be on their market share and that the popular press would be overjoyed to take up James's cause.

snippet.textDisplay:
actually, the courts would not agree with Peter. If you use a name, even your own, that plays off of a much larger well known company, you will lose in court. If your last name is McDonald and you started a hamburger joint called McDonald's you would lose if sued. You can be denied use of your name if the judge rules that your name is intended to play off of a more successful company. Same thing with fonts or colors of famous brands.


On dragon's Den canada, a woman came in with a name of an auto garage called Ms Lube, which was a play on Mr Lube, famous chain of oil change places. She was forced out of business with that name.
